  "body": "<!--üíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíé\r\n\r\nHellooo! üòÑ \r\n\r\nTo help us tend to your issue faster, please search our currently open issues before submitting a new one.\r\nExisting issues often contain information about workarounds, resolution, or progress updates.\r\n\r\nüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíéüíé-->\r\n\r\n# üêû Bug Report\r\n\r\n### Description\r\n\r\nGiven an `eth1HeaderReqLimit` of 1000 it's very easy for log processing to exceed the get_Logs limit of some common web3 providers (e.g. infura limits at 10,000). I believe these types of web3 providers will be a common alternative to running one's own eth1 node. \r\n\r\n### Has this worked before in a previous version?\r\n\r\nWasn't as much of an issue when running a Medalla beacon-chain node\r\n\r\n## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction\r\n\r\nRun a Pyrmont beacon-chain node with a Infura or similar web3-http-provider\r\n\r\n## üî• Error\r\n\r\n<pre><code>\r\ntime=\"2020-11-18 17:33:24\" level=error msg=\"Unable to process past logs query returned more than 10000 results\" prefix=powchain\r\n\r\ntime=\"2020-11-18 22:11:48\" level=error msg=\"Could not connect to powchain endpoint\" error=\"could not dial eth1 nodes: 429 Too Many Requests: {\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":1,\"error\":{\"code\":-32005,\"message\":\"daily request count exceeded, request rate limited\",\"data\":{\"rate\":{\"allowed_rps\":1,\"backoff_seconds\":27,\"current_rps\":1.1333333333333333},\"see\":\"https://infura.io/dashboard\"}}}\" prefix=powchain\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**What version of Prysm are you running? (Which release)**\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nv1.0.0-beta.3\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n**Anything else relevant (validator index / public key)?**\r\n\r\n",
